article.description: Tracy McGrady shook off a poor start to score 32 points, Mike James gave host Houston a huge lift off the bench and the Rockets won their fifth straight game Saturday night, 115-87 over the streaking Denver Nuggets.
article.headline: Denver's 10 game win streak disappears

images.name: McGrady_Tracy 050416 inline
images.caption: McGrady's 32 points led six Rockets in double figures.

article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- How hard is it to stop Tracy McGrady? Not even George Karl and the streaking Denver Nuggets could come up with anything. "When a guy like Tracy gets hot, there really isn't much you can do to stop him," Nuggets forward Carmelo Anthony said. McGrady shook off a poor start to score 32 points, Mike James gave Houston a huge lift off the bench and the Rockets won their fifth straight game Saturday night, 115-87 over the Nuggets for their worst loss of the season. James scored 23 points, Yao Ming had 13 points, 11 rebounds and five blocks and his backup, Dikembe Mutombo, added 11 points, 12 rebounds and three blocks to help the Rockets end the Nuggets' 10-game winning streak in a Western Conference showdown critical to playoff positioning. "I think the last few games have been a good chance for us to play our game," Yao said. "Today was a good way for us to prepare for the pressure that we will see in the playoffs." With two games left before the postseason, the Rockets (49-31) wrestled away control of sixth place in the West and now hold a tiebreaker over the Nuggets (48-32) in case they finish with the same record. Houston also moved a half-game behind Sacramento for the No. 5 seed. The Kings played at league-leading Phoenix on Saturday night. The Rockets will close the season with home games against the Los Angeles Clippers on Monday night and Seattle on Wednesday night. The Nuggets play at Phoenix on Monday night and end with a home game against Portland on Tuesday night. Kenyon Martin led the Nuggets with 22 points and nine rebounds, the first time in nine games that Anthony didn't lead Denver in scoring. Anthony had 16 points on 4-of-17 shooting. The Nuggets definitely could have used starting center Marcus Camby, who sat out because of a strained right hamstring. Without its top defender and rebounder, Denver was especially vulnerable to the Rockets' suddenly diverse offensive attack. "Our reliance on Marcus is pretty clear," Karl said. "I mean, we're a different team when Marcus is in there against a good team. We have to make sure we get him healthy." Minutes before the game, though, Karl warned that he wasn't going to allow McGrady to singlehandedly beat his team. "If I have my plan straight, it won't be McGrady that beats us," Karl said then. "Someone else will beat us." But McGrady started attacking the teeth of the Nuggets' defense after making only one of his first eight shots, and eventually had his way with a variety of defenders ranging from point guard Andre Miller to Anthony and even the 6-foot-9, 234-pound Martin. McGrady, who scored 45 points in a Jan. 9 win over Denver, also opened up things for his teammates, who combined to tie a season high with 15 3-pointers on 63-percent shooting. McGrady even turned up the intensity on other end of the floor, frustrating Anthony with unusually aggressive defense -- at least for him. "I thought we had decent control on McGrady," Karl said, "then he blew up on us. We allowed a great player to take over the game." Coming off a 111-102 win over Memphis on Friday night, the Nuggets looked nothing like a team in the second night of grueling back-to-back games -- in the game's early minutes. Denver raced out to an 18-4 lead and led by 10 at the end of the first quarter. But led by their reserves, the Rockets made a furious rally before the end of the half. Mutombo made two free throws to give Houston its first lead of the night, 43-41, with 4:34 left in the second. McGrady closed the half with consecutive 3s, the last on a nifty behind-the-back assist from Jon Barry, to put the Rockets up 56-49 at the break. The bench "did a great job of getting us back into striking distance," Rockets coach Jeff Van Gundy said. The Rockets eventually wore down the plodding Nuggets at the end, scoring the first six points of the fourth quarter to take an 86-70 lead. McGrady punctuated the win by crossing over Denver forward Eduardo Najera, causing him to stumble before hitting a 3-pointer that gave Houston a 19-point lead with a little more than 9 minutes left. The Nuggets never got any closer after that. "It was tough," Anthony said. "It hasn't been like that since early in the season. This loss may wake up and now we can feel what the teams we were beating up on felt like."

Game notes
Houston is the only team other than Phoenix to beat Denver in the past 27 games. ... Denver guard Greg Buckner played after missing the previous three games with a fracture in his right hand. He had six points in 19 minutes. ... The Rockets' reserves scored a season-high 56 points. ... With 13 more points, McGrady will join Elvin Hayes, Moses Malone and Hakeem Olajuwon as the only other Rockets to score 2,000 points in a season. ... Swimming star Michael Phelps, who won eight medals in the Athens Olympics, and Illinois junior guard Deron Williams, who is considering entering the NBA draft, were among those in the sellout crowd.
